{
  "texts": [
    "Reachability distance (RD) of a data point p to the data point x, is defined as the maximum of k-distance of x and the distance between point p and x, d(p, x), which is calculated using Euclidean distance.",
    "For example, in Fig. 6, we take k = 3, the k nearest neighbors of instance x will be N k (x) = {p 1, p 2, p 3 }.",
    "So the value of ||N 3 (x)|| = 3.",
    "If the distance between data point p 3 and",
    "(3) RD(p, x) = max{k-distance(x), d(p, x)} Fig. 6 An example demonstrating LOF and calculating reachability distance of data points data point x is smaller than the k-distance (x), the reachability distance of data point p 3 is replaced by k-distance(x)."
  ]
}